<br>
Heck, no, its not too powerful. Think of how silly it works WITHOUT it. Any security guard can go back and review the tapes and go &quot;OHMIGOD, that guy's a friggin' monster! I outta call the 6 o'clock news!&quot; <br>
<br>
Doesn't this sound like a Masquerade breach? Wouldn't it make sense to say that the Nosferatu, spies extraordinare, would come up with some way of defeating it?<br>
<br>
Just my own opinion.<br>
<br>
Mike <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=isaacstone>Isaac Stone</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#FF9300>(7/28/03 7:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=60.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: False Reflection</span><hr size=1> why don't you tell us why you feel it is too powerful?  <br>
<br>
I think the fact you have to spend a mental trait, which to me means you have to know that you are being recorded, seems a good enough limit.  It's weaker then Iron Will or Unbondable, and doesn't seem to be munchkin bait, (no additional traits or retests).  The Storyteller can always pay off the Merit, or not allow it for players or character concepts.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=grooish>Grooish</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>William Garcia</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#FF9300>(7/29/03 7:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=60.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: False Reflection</span><hr size=1> I think that it could be view as too powerful because with<br>
a bit of forethought it can be used to screw over just about<br>
anybody in the mortal world.<br>
<br>
Example: I'm Ned the Nos, and I hate Timmy the Toreador. I have<br>
the merit in question and I decide it's time for Timmy to get some<br>
bad press. Consequently I alter my electronic appearance and go on<br>
a carefully planned murder spree (making sure camera's are around,<br>
not hard in this day and age.) making sure that the most revolting,<br>
shocking and enraging aspects of these crimes are caught on tape. Now,<br>
the police jump into called into action, normally not caring about such<br>
things but given how the whole event has been caught on tape, leaked to<br>
the media the police now mobilize all of their resources to get this <br>
Timmy Taylor guy and lock him up in a cell with a nice westerly <br>
exposure. ... Ned laughs over Timmy's demise all the way to the sewers.<br>
<br>
With a little bit of effort most any target of such a smear campaign would <br>
have to abandon their mortal IDs. Hence this little three point merit could <br>
be too powerful in the hands of certain methodical players.<br>
<br>
<br>
         Jake<br>
